# AtpClient + KinoAtpClient demo

```elixir
Mix.install([
  {:kino_atp_client, "~> 0.5"}
])
```

## LocalExec: prove a TPTP problem with the bundled E prover

```elixir
Application.put_env(:atp_client, :local_exec,
  binary: "eprover",
  args: ["--auto", "--tstp-format", "--cpu-limit=10"],
  cpu_timeout_s: 10
)

problem = """
fof(tautology, conjecture, (p => p)).
"""

AtpClient.LocalExec.query(problem, [])
```

## Isabelle: prove a lemma via the resident server

The container's MCP launcher starts an Isabelle server (`atp`, port 9999)
and writes its password to `/workspace/.isabelle_server_info`. If you
haven't started Claude Code in this container yet, start the server by
hand first: `isabelle server -n atp -p 9999 &` and note the printed
password.

```elixir
password =
  "/workspace/.isabelle_server_info"
  |> File.read!()
  |> String.split("\n", trim: true)
  |> Enum.find_value(fn
    "password=" <> pw -> pw
    _ -> nil
  end)

Application.put_env(:atp_client, :isabelle,
  host: "127.0.0.1",
  port: 9999,
  password: password,
  session: "HOL"
)

theory = ~S"""
lemma "P \<or> \<not> P" by auto
"""

AtpClient.Isabelle.query(theory, "Example", [])
```

## Smart cells

With `kino_atp_client` installed, the *"+ Smart"* cell menu offers the
AtpClient smart cells — see the package's own `examples/demo.livemd` in
`jcschuster/KinoAtpClient` for the full tour.
